                "href": "/profile/Chris-Cooling-1"
            },
            "answer_text": "The playing of the DVD has no effect on its lifespan and causes no wear. However, given enough time the DVD polycarbonate layers will likely begin to separate, exposing the data layer to oxygen, thus slowly destroying the data stored on it. This happened to many of my early double sided DVDs from New Line and Warner. I ended up getting rid of all my early titles as better re-releases came out. As a disc repair person for a chain, I saw this was common among releases from the 90s. This article explains more about CD/DVD disc rot. ",
